<p class="p">The degree of comfort for mammals like dairy cows has traditionally been evaluated using THI, which is estimated from dry bulb and wet bulb temperatures, dew point temperatures, or relative humidity [
 <xref rid="pone.0214665.ref020" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">20</xref>]. In this study, we calculated THI using the method proposed by Yousef [
 <xref rid="pone.0214665.ref040" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">40</xref>] for cattle [Eqs (
 <xref ref-type="disp-formula" rid="pone.0214665.e001" class="xref">1</xref>) and (
 <xref ref-type="disp-formula" rid="pone.0214665.e002" class="xref">2</xref>)] to accommodate the available projected data. This THI method uses daily mean dew point temperature (Tdew
 <sub class="sub">d</sub>) as a proxy for daily relative humidity, and was applied by Key and Sneering [
 <xref rid="pone.0214665.ref016" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">16</xref>] to evaluate climate change impacts on dairy production across the continental U.S. We used maximum and minimum daily temperature (Tmax
 <sub class="sub">d</sub> and Tmin
 <sub class="sub">d</sub>) to estimate maximum and minimum daily THI (THImax
 <sub class="sub">d</sub> and THImin
 <sub class="sub">d</sub>): 
